### What the test demands precisely

The test calls `applyBenchmarkTask(runData, now)` and checks the returned view AND mutations persisted into `runData`. Framework: **`node:assert` (`strictEqual`/`deepStrictEqual`) run directly by `node`** — no jest/mocha/vitest. Any assertion failure throws and aborts (exit non-zero); success prints the final `console.log`.

The returned object from `applyBenchmarkTask` (which delegates to `buildPortalView`) must produce:
- `status` === `"At-risk escalation active with executive recovery owner routing and customer-visible audit history."`
- `owner` === `expectedOwners.join(" + ")` → `"Customer Success + Support + Finance + Executive Sponsor"`
- `nextStep.length > 8`
- `history` === `"Audit visible"` (requires a `customerVisible` audit event)
- `customerMessage.length > 12`
- `riskSummary` === `"6 signals: strategic, account, rescue, enterprise account, open customer impact, audit required"`
- `tasks` === `"4 owner tasks"`

Persisted-state requirements (mutations to `runData`):
- `workflow_state`: push one doc with `requestId === request._id` (`"account-strategic-ac"`), `status` === expectedStatus, `title`, `nextStep`, and `riskSignals` (array of objects whose `.name` deep-equals the 6 fixture signal names in order).
- `owner_tasks`: push exactly 4 docs, each with `requestId`, `ownerGroup` matching the 4 ownerGroups **in order**, plus truthy `title`, truthy `dueAt`, and `status === "open"`.
- `customer_messages`: push at least one doc with matching `requestId` and a truthy `body`.
- `audit_events`: push at least one doc with matching `requestId` and `customerVisible` truthy.

Because `buildPortalView` derives the view from these persisted collections, the implementation only needs to write the documents correctly and the view falls out automatically.

